  "text": "The model generates a stochastic amount of manure produced by individual cows. [CITATION_1] provides a mean and standard deviation of the amount of manure produced by different livestock species and the components of each species' manure. A normal distribution of manure produced per head per day constructed using data from [CITATION_2]  x − = 190 lb., s = 37 lb. for lactating animals, x − = 104 lb., s = 20 lb. for dry) is multiplied by the number of cows in each of the lactating and dry cow categories to obtain the total daily pounds of manure produced on each dairy. In order to introduce variability into the biogas system's output amount, a stochastic element was added to the amount of solids converted to biogas as a percent, and the cubic feet of biogas per pound of volatile solids converted. The model assumes a uniform distribution from 10.0% above and 10.0% below the expected values of both figures that are important in determining the amount of electricity the AD generates and reflect real-life variability in system output based on fluctuation in management decisions by operating staff. [CITATION_3] suggest that daily management decisions are key in the overall efficiency and amount of biogas produced by a biogas generation system.",
